<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Corporate_history">Corporate history</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bain_%26_Company&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Corporate history">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Establishment">Establishment</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bain_%26_Company&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Establishment">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The idea for Bain &amp; Company was conceived by co-founder William Worthington Bain Jr. during his time at the <a href="/wiki/Boston_Consulting_Group" title="Boston Consulting Group">Boston Consulting Group</a> (BCG).<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> In 1970, BCG CEO <a href="/wiki/Bruce_Henderson" title="Bruce Henderson">Bruce Henderson</a> decided to divide his firm into three competing mini-firms: blue, red, and green. Bill Bain and Patrick Graham headed the blue team.<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> The blue team accounted for over half of BCG's revenue and profits and won the internal competition. After the competition, Bill Bain grew increasingly frustrated by the wait for Henderson's retirement, the firm's project-based approach to consulting, and the refusal of management to help clients execute on the firm's advice.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> Around this time, he is quoted to have said to feel like "a consultant on a desert island, writing a report, putting it in a bottle, throwing it in the water, then going on to the next one."<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Bain was the expected successor of Henderson within BCG in the early 70s.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> However, in 1973, three years after Henderson's competing team decision, Bill Bain resigned to start his own consulting firm.<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">&#91;a&#93;</a></sup> Most of the senior members of the "blue team" followed him to his newfound company, which was started from his apartment in the <a href="/wiki/Beacon_Hill,_Boston" title="Beacon Hill, Boston">Beacon Hill neighborhood</a> of Boston.<sup id="cite_ref-vault_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-vault-15">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> A significant part of firms for which he was responsible at BCG also followed Bain to the new company. Within a few weeks, Bain &amp; Company was working with seven former BCG clients;<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> this included two of BCG's largest clients, <a href="/wiki/Black_%26_Decker" class="mw-redirect" title="Black &amp; Decker">Black &amp; Decker</a> and <a href="/wiki/Texas_Instruments" title="Texas Instruments">Texas Instruments</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Bloomberg.com_1991_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bloomberg.com_1991-16">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> As a result, Henderson accused Bill of stealing BCG's clientele.<sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> It is believed that the competition Henderson put out laid the foundation for Bain &amp; Company.<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Bain &amp; Company grew quickly,<sup id="cite_ref-journal_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-journal-17">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> primarily through word-of-mouth among CEOs and board members.<sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_1987_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fortune_1987-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> The firm established its first formal office in Boston.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> This was followed by a European office in London in 1979.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> Bain &amp; Company was incorporated in 1985.<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> The firm grew an average of 50 percent per year, reaching $150 million in revenues by 1986.<sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_1987_18-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fortune_1987-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> The number of staff at the firm tripled from 1980 to 1986, reaching 800 in 1987.<sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_1987_18-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fortune_1987-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> By 1987, Bain &amp; Company was one of the four largest "strategy specialist" consulting firms.<sup id="cite_ref-journal_17-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-journal-17">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> Employee turnover was 8 percent annually compared to an industry average of 20 percent.<sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_1987_18-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fortune_1987-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> Some of the firm's largest clients in this period were <a href="/wiki/National_Steel_Corporation" title="National Steel Corporation">National Steel</a> and <a href="/wiki/Chrysler" title="Chrysler">Chrysler</a>, each of which reduced manufacturing costs with Bain's help.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Turmoil">Turmoil</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bain_%26_Company&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Turmoil">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In the late 1980s, Bain &amp; Company experienced a series of setbacks.<sup id="cite_ref-Bloomberg.com_1991_16-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bloomberg.com_1991-16">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> A public relations crisis emerged in 1987, due to a controversy involving Bain's work with <a href="/wiki/Guinness" title="Guinness">Guinness</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> Tension was growing over the firm's partnership structure, whereby only Bain knew how much the firm was making and decided how much profit-sharing each partner received.<sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_1987_18-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fortune_1987-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> The stock market crashed the same year, and many Bain clients reduced or eliminated their spending with the firm.<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> There were two rounds of layoffs, eliminating about 30 percent of the workforce.<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Bloomberg.com_1991_16-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bloomberg.com_1991-16">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">&#91;b&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Guinness_share-trading_fraud" title="Guinness share-trading fraud">Guinness share-trading fraud</a> began with Britain's Department of Trade and Industry investigating whether Bain's client Guinness illegally inflated its stock price.<sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> Bain had helped Guinness trim 150 companies from its portfolio after a period of excessive diversification<sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_1987_18-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fortune_1987-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> and expand into hard liquor with the acquisition of two whiskey companies,<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> growing profits six-fold.<sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_1987_18-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fortune_1987-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> During this time, Bain made an exception to company policy by allowing a consultant to serve as an interim board member and head of finance for Guinness.<sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_1987_18-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fortune_1987-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> Bain &amp; Company was not accused of any wrongdoing and no charges were pressed against Bain<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> for the manipulation of the stock price, but having a Bain consultant work as both vendor and client drew criticisms of Bain's handling of a conflict of interest situation.<sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_1987_18-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fortune_1987-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 1985 and 1986, Bain &amp; Company took out loans to buy 30 percent of the firm from Bain and other partners for $200 million and used the shares to create an Employee Stock Ownership Plan (ESOP).<sup id="cite_ref-Bloomberg.com_1991_16-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bloomberg.com_1991-16">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Washington_Post_2012_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Washington_Post_2012-21">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> These shares of the company were bought at five times Bain &amp; Company's annual revenue, more than double the norm, and cost the firm $25 million in annual interest fees, exacerbating the firm's financial troubles.<sup id="cite_ref-Bloomberg.com_1991_16-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bloomberg.com_1991-16">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> Bain hired former U.S. Army general <a href="/wiki/Pete_Dawkins" title="Pete Dawkins">Pete Dawkins</a> as the head of North America in hopes that new leadership could bring about a turnaround, but Dawkins' leadership led to even more turnover at the firm.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> Bill Bain also attempted to sell the firm but was unsuccessful at finding a buyer.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Rebound">Rebound</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bain_%26_Company&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Rebound">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p><a href="/wiki/Mitt_Romney" title="Mitt Romney">Mitt Romney</a> was hired back as interim CEO of Bain &amp; Company in January 1991<sup id="cite_ref-Washington_Post_2012_21-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Washington_Post_2012-21">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> and is credited with saving the company from bankruptcy during his one-year stint in the position.<sup id="cite_ref-Groth_Lubin_2011_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Groth_Lubin_2011-22">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Rifkin_1994_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rifkin_1994-23">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> Romney originally left Bain &amp; Company in 1983 after appointed by Bain to lead <a href="/wiki/Bain_Capital" title="Bain Capital">Bain Capital</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">&#91;c&#93;</a></sup> an independent private equity firm that would buy companies that Bain &amp; Company partners would improve and re-sell<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> and whose funds these partners invested in.<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> Romney allowed managers to know each other's salaries,<sup id="cite_ref-Groth_Lubin_2011_22-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Groth_Lubin_2011-22">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup> re-negotiated the firm's debt,<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> and restructured the organization so more partners had an ownership stake in the firm.<sup id="cite_ref-Bloomberg.com_1991_16-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bloomberg.com_1991-16">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> Romney convinced the founding partners to give up $100 million in equity.<sup id="cite_ref-Washington_Post_2012_21-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Washington_Post_2012-21">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> Bain and most of the founding partners left the firm.<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Orit_Gadiesh.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/Orit_Gadiesh.jpg/220px-Orit_Gadiesh.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="151" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/Orit_Gadiesh.jpg/330px-Orit_Gadiesh.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/Orit_Gadiesh.jpg/440px-Orit_Gadiesh.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="550" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Orit_Gadiesh.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Orit Gadiesh</div></div></div>
<p>Romney left again in December 1992 to pursue a career in politics,<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> but not before he organized an election of new leaders the following year, leading to the appointment of <a href="/wiki/Orit_Gadiesh" title="Orit Gadiesh">Orit Gadiesh</a> as Chairman and <a href="/wiki/Thomas_J._Tierney" title="Thomas J. Tierney">Thomas J. Tierney</a> as Worldwide Managing Director in July 1993.<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Sinclair_2013_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Sinclair_2013-27">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup> Gadiesh improved morale and loosened the firm's policy against working with multiple companies in the same industry in order to decrease the firm's reliance on a small number of clients.<sup id="cite_ref-Rifkin_1994_23-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rifkin_1994-23">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> Gadiesh has been serving as Chairman ever since. By the end of 1993, Bain &amp; Company was growing once again.<sup id="cite_ref-vault_15-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-vault-15">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Rifkin_1994_23-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rifkin_1994-23">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> The firm went from 1,000 employees at its peak, to 550 in 1991, and back up to 800.<sup id="cite_ref-Rifkin_1994_23-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rifkin_1994-23">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> The firm opened more offices, including one in New York in 2000.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> From 1992 through 1999, the firm grew 25 percent per year and expanded from 12 to 26 offices.<sup id="cite_ref-consultingmag.com_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-consultingmag.com-28">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> By 1998, the firm had $220 million in annual revenues and 700 staff.<sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Recent_history">Recent history</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bain_%26_Company&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Recent history">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Bain created two technology consulting practice groups, bainlab and BainNet, in 1999 and 2000 respectively.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> bainlab was originally founded as Bain New Venture Group.<sup id="cite_ref-doaufhd_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-doaufhd-29">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> It helped startups who otherwise might not afford Bain's fees and accepted partial payment in equity.<sup id="cite_ref-doaufhd_29-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-doaufhd-29">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> In February 2000, Gadiesh was elected for her third consecutive term as the firm's chairman, and Tom Tierney was replaced by <a href="/wiki/John_Donahoe" title="John Donahoe">John Donahoe</a> as managing director.<sup id="cite_ref-vault_15-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-vault-15">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> Around 2000, the firm became more involved in consulting private equity firms on which companies to invest in and collaborating with technology consulting firms.<sup id="cite_ref-consultingmag.com_28-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-consultingmag.com-28">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> By 2005, Bain had the largest share of the market for private equity consulting.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Economistt_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Economistt-30">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup> By 2018, Bain's Private Equity group was over three times as large as that of the next largest consulting firm serving Private Equity firms and represented 25% of Bain's global business.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Bain &amp; Company does not publish its revenues, but it is estimated to have experienced double-digit annual growth in the 2000s.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Economistt_30-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Economistt-30">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup> Although the market for management consulting was declining, the Big Three management consulting firms, including Bain &amp; Company, continued to grow.<sup id="cite_ref-Stern2010_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Stern2010-32">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> Bain expanded to new offices in other countries,<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> including India in 2006.<sup id="cite_ref-Mahanta_2006_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mahanta_2006-33">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Business_News_2007_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Business_News_2007-34">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> Like the other big consulting firms, it began working more with governments.<sup id="cite_ref-Stern2010_32-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Stern2010-32">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> Bain maintained a "generalist" approach to management consulting but created a separate specialist business unit for IT and technology.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Economistt_30-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Economistt-30">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup> In 2012, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Robert_Bechek&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Robert Bechek (page does not exist)">Robert Bechek</a> was appointed CEO and was later ranked as the most-liked CEO in Glassdoor employee surveys.<sup id="cite_ref-Washington_Post_2016_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Washington_Post_2016-35">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup> On November 20, 2017, Bain announced that Bob Bechek would step down as the worldwide managing director. Emmanuel P. "Manny" Maceda, eldest son of the late <a href="/wiki/Filipinos" title="Filipinos">Filipino</a> politician <a href="/wiki/Ernesto_Maceda" title="Ernesto Maceda">Ernesto Maceda</a>, was elected to succeed Bechek as the worldwide managing director effective March 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-GlobalNewsWire_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GlobalNewsWire-37">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup> In an interview with the <i><a href="/wiki/Financial_Times" title="Financial Times">Financial Times</a></i>, Maceda announced a focus on the expansion of Bain's digital practice. He began by leading Bain to its first true acquisition: in 2018, the firm purchased the Minneapolis-based marketing agency FRWD, in an effort to continue growing the firm's practice areas.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="South_African_Revenue_Service_Inquiry">South African Revenue Service Inquiry</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bain_%26_Company&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: South African Revenue Service Inquiry">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In late 2018, a new South African government investigated the <a href="/wiki/South_African_Revenue_Service" title="South African Revenue Service">South African Revenue Service</a> (SARS) for suspected corruption under the administration of former President <a href="/wiki/Jacob_Zuma" title="Jacob Zuma">Jacob Zuma</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-The_New_York_Times_2018_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_New_York_Times_2018-39">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> It found that in 2015 Bain &amp; Company billed $11 million for consulting projects, where the firm gave bad advice.<sup id="cite_ref-The_New_York_Times_2018_39-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_New_York_Times_2018-39">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> After interviewing just 33 employees over six days,<sup id="cite_ref-The_New_York_Times_2018_39-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_New_York_Times_2018-39">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> Bain provided a restructuring plan that included downsizing the SARS Business Centre, which produced one-third of the tax agency's revenues.<sup id="cite_ref-Umraw_2018_40-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Umraw_2018-40">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup> An investigation found that then-SARS head Tom Moyane followed an unusual procurement process favoring Bain, who Moyane had been in touch with before his appointment at SARS.<sup id="cite_ref-Marrian_2018_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Marrian_2018-41">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Critics claimed Bain intentionally collaborated in then-President Zuma's corrupt acts to favor his wealthy allies and help Zuma avoid taxes, contributing to a dysfunctional tax agency in the process.<sup id="cite_ref-The_New_York_Times_2018_39-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_New_York_Times_2018-39">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> Bain claimed the consulting firm was an unintentional pawn in Zuma's conspiracies working under the head of the tax agency,  a Zuma collaborator, that hand-picked the SARS employees Bain interviewed.<sup id="cite_ref-The_New_York_Times_2018_39-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_New_York_Times_2018-39">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> SARS officials said Bain's reports were based on false and outdated information and that senior SARS officials were not consulted.<sup id="cite_ref-Khumalo_2018_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Khumalo_2018-42">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup> Bain replaced its executive in South Africa and offered to refund the consulting fees.<sup id="cite_ref-Marrian_20182_43-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Marrian_20182-43">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The inquiry recommended that the South African National Director of Public Prosecutions (NDPP) institute criminal proceedings in connection with the award of the consulting contract to Bain &amp; Company.<sup id="cite_ref-Umraw_2018_40-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Umraw_2018-40">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Consulting_services">Consulting services</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bain_%26_Company&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Consulting services">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Bain &amp; Company provides management consulting services primarily to Fortune 500 CEOs.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> The firm advises on issues such as private equity investments, mergers &amp; acquisitions, corporate strategy, finance, operations, and market analysis.<sup id="cite_ref-wetfeet_44-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wetfeet-44">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup> It also has departments focused on customer loyalty, word of mouth marketing, and digital technology.<sup id="cite_ref-Bain_&amp;_Companyhistory_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bain_&amp;_Companyhistory-45">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup> Most of its consulting is on corporate strategy.<sup id="cite_ref-book_46-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-book-46">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2000, The <a href="/wiki/Bridgespan_Group" title="Bridgespan Group">Bridgespan Group</a> was created to work with non-profits and to facilitate pro-bono work for staff.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> Bain &amp; Company also maintains an in-house social impact practice and pledged in 2015 to invest $1 billion in pro bono consulting by 2025.<sup id="cite_ref-Willy_Foote_47-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Willy_Foote-47">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Vault2018_48-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Vault2018-48">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> This practice is built upon different pillars, including social and economic development, climate change, education, and local community development. Organizations that Bain has supported through pro-bono work include <a href="/wiki/UNHCR" class="mw-redirect" title="UNHCR">UNHCR</a>, the <a href="/wiki/World_Childhood_Foundation" title="World Childhood Foundation">World Childhood Foundation</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Teach_for_America" class="mw-redirect" title="Teach for America">Teach for America</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-CFReport_49-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CFReport-49">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Bain_Social_Impact_50-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bain_Social_Impact-50">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup> Bain's pro-bono work was in 2015 awarded by Consulting Magazine as a winner of their Excellence in Social and Community Investment Awards for having "redefined how companies approach corporate social responsibility."<sup id="cite_ref-GNW_51-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GNW-51">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Later in the 2000s, Bain introduced service packages for specific areas of expertise, such as the supply chain.<sup id="cite_ref-directory_11-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-directory-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> The firm also became more heavily involved in consulting with private equity firms, advising on what companies to buy, facilitating a turnaround, and then re-selling the company.<sup id="cite_ref-The_Economistt_30-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_Economistt-30">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup> In early 2006, Bain started selling its "net-promoter score" system, which tracks customer sentiment.<sup id="cite_ref-Kranhold_2006_52-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kranhold_2006-52">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Reception">Reception</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bain_%26_Company&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Reception">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>According to <i>The New York Times</i>, the results of Bain's consulting "have often been impressive."<sup id="cite_ref-reception_1_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reception_1-53">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup> An audit by <a href="/wiki/Price_Waterhouse" class="mw-redirect" title="Price Waterhouse">Price Waterhouse</a> found that the aggregate market value of Bain clients increased 456 percent from 1980 to 1989, whereas the Dow Jones industrial average increased 192 percent during the same time period.<sup id="cite_ref-reception_1_53-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reception_1-53">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-reception_2_54-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reception_2-54">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup> Bain promises clients it will not work with competitors but in exchange requires that the client commit to a long-term engagement.<sup id="cite_ref-reception_3_55-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reception_3-55">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup> The firm's approach to non-competition was unique and helped Bain grow through word-of-mouth among corporate boardrooms.<sup id="cite_ref-reception_4_56-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reception_4-56">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup> However, since Bain insists on long-term engagements and implements the advice they provide, competitors claim Bain preys on insecure CEOs that are looking to outsource their jobs.<sup id="cite_ref-reception_42_57-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reception_42-57">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup> In some cases, Bain's billings increase every year, but the client becomes so dependent, and the firm so embedded in the client's operations, that Bain becomes unfirable.<sup id="cite_ref-reception_5_58-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-reception_5-58">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Corporate_culture">Corporate culture</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bain_%26_Company&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Corporate culture">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Bain &amp; Company is known for being secretive.<sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_1987_18-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fortune_1987-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> The firm is sometimes referred to as the "KGB of Consulting."<sup id="cite_ref-Kiechel_2010_p._224_13-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kiechel_2010_p._224-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-book_46-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-book-46">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup> Clients are given codenames.<sup id="cite_ref-economist_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-economist-59">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup> Employees must sign nondisclosure contracts, promising not to reveal client names, and are required to adhere to a "code of confidentiality."<sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Bain employees are sometimes called "Bainies."<sup id="cite_ref-wetfeet_44-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wetfeet-44">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup> It was originally a pejorative term but was adopted by employees as an affectionate term.<sup id="cite_ref-wetfeet_44-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wetfeet-44">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup> According to <i>Fortune</i>, were Bain &amp; Company a person, "it would be articulate, attractive, meticulously well groomed, and exceedingly charming. It would exude Southern gentility. But it would also be a shrewd, intensely ambitious strategist, totally in control."<sup id="cite_ref-Fortune_1987_18-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fortune_1987-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Bain is often placed among the top best places to work in annual rankings by <a href="/wiki/Glassdoor" title="Glassdoor">Glassdoor</a><sup id="cite_ref-Weller_Jacobs_2016_60-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Weller_Jacobs_2016-60">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup> and <i>Consulting Magazine</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-Consulting_Magazine_2013_61-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Consulting_Magazine_2013-61">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup> Bain primarily hires MBAs from business schools,<sup id="cite_ref-Gallese_1989_12-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gallese_1989-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> but it is one of the first firms to hire consultants with a bachelor's degree.<sup id="cite_ref-book_46-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-book-46">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup> The firm is organized primarily by geographic office, with each location acting somewhat independently.<sup id="cite_ref-book_46-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-book-46">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup> It also has a mix of overlapping functional (such as M&amp;A, technology, or loyalty) and industry (financial services, healthcare, etc.) teams.<sup id="cite_ref-book_46-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-book-46">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup> An elected worldwide managing director is allowed up to three, three-year terms under the firm's bylaws.<sup id="cite_ref-consultingmag.com_28-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-consultingmag.com-28">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Bain_%26_Company&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
